result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Cases 16CF222 and 16CM112 called together at 1:40pm [ma]
Defendant Nathanael T. Stubbs in court with Attorney Elizabeth F Svehlek.  Susan Victoria Happ appears for the State of Wisconsin.
  
Maximum penalties recited; Constitutional rights reviewed; plea of " GUILTY " entered Case 16CF222, Count #1, #2, and #3; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance verified; the Court accepts the plea, finds Defendant guilty, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

On Motion of the State, the Court reads-in and dismisses: Remaining Counts of 16CF222 and 16CM112

Sentencing arguments given by Counsel
Statement made by Mr. Stubbs

On Case 16CF222, Count #1, #2, and #3, the Court withholds sentence, and places Defendant on Probation for 5 years, with conditions:

--On Count #1:to serve 6 months in the Jefferson County Jail, with Huber/work-release privileges, to commence on 1/2/17 at 900am
---Mr. Stubbs is required to report for commencement and service of jail sentence with absolute sobriety and without non-prescribed controlled substances in system; non-compliance will result in loss of work-release privileges without further process.

--to undergo AODA assessment and follow through with recommended treatment
--to undergo any other assessment, treatment, or counseling as deemed appropriate by the Agent
--to maintain employment and/or education program as approved by the Agent
--maintain absolute sobriety
--no possession of drug paraphernalia
--no possession or consumption of illegal drugs
--no presence in bars, taverns, or liquor stores
--drug testing per Agent
--to pay statutory costs
--to pay drug testing fees as followed: $150 to JCSTF and $25 to FAPD
--to pay buy money in the amount of $760 to JCDTF
--provide DNA sample upon demand

Days credit for time already served:  1  day
